snippet.textDisplay:
* Not everyone has suitable accommodation in the UK to isolate and millions are forced to live in shared scenarios.
.* 8 million live in inadequate accommodation: bed and breakfasts, hostels, emergency accommodation, bedsits with shared toilets & showers
* it's allot to ask someone to stay in their one roomed flat without television and just a microwave for 14 days, especially if they haven't got the facilities to store much if any food.
* Once I was put in emergency accommodation in Eastbourne (even though I lived in Brighton) and it didn't have any cooking facilities, and not even a fridge. There was no shared kitchen either. It was just one very small room. What is someone in those circumstances to do?
* There's an unknown, seriously under-estimated number - many thousands - of homeless people. We don't know how many they are because the method of counting seems intentionally designed to perpetually underestimate the figures. Do you know how they count? They go out looking for homeless people in each town, at night, clearly not looking everywhere and allot of homeless people prefer to be well hidden. They will miss those also who are maybe in pubs or clubs, which are open all ours where I live in Brighton, or those staying in back packer hostels and the like. They don't even collect data from, or cross-check with, local services. Once I saw the figures for Brighton, some years back and they were '33'. I knew full well there was hundreds of homeless people because I was involved with the services at the time and there were so many homeless people you hardly saw the same face twice even though you saw them every day months on end.
* we're going to pay severely for the chronic deterioration in services, support & social safety nets that has taken place over the years - our total failure Io look after each other over the past four decades, and the appalling selfishness and brutal individualism that has taken root since thatcher said there is no such thing as society.
* If we were a co-operative society before the breakdown of supply chains & services, we would pull together, help each other out & share & ration: it wouldn't be such a problem. A society that is selfish and self-seeking, and doesn't care about the neighbor who is isolated alone or the homeless person on the street, is going to be in dire straights as it won't pull together and people won't act in the best interests of all. We are an individualistic, and generally rather selfish, judgemental society: we are all going to be out for ourselves, a war all against all, people having fist fights over toilet paper, there being murders over food.
* Unconciously we all anticipate an approaching total breakdown of our system of civilization, owing to the climate emergency and the many problems stemming from the rampant environmental destruction, including mass migration. I've heard one estimate from an expert that there could be one billion displaced people: apparently there are already a hundred million. There are 52 million people right now facing critical levels of hunger in Africa alone, according to The Guardian, and millions of these are because of the astonishing rate of desertification blamed on climate change. Lake Chad was the chief source of water for a whole nation, and it has reduced by an unbelievable 90% over the past few decades leading to mass migration. Last year 30 million died of starvation or malnutrition, and we let this happen. A child dies of starvation or malnutrition every 2 seconds. Is it nationalism and individualism that has lead us to let the problems of the world build up like this to the point that they will become insurmountable? It seems it's only when the problems approach our front door that we will act, by which time it'll be way too late. It's certainly far too late for the hundreds of millions whose lives have been devastated already by the effects of our destructive and inhuman social order.

snippet.textDisplay:
Two years ago, I retired from working in clinical respiratory care for 38 years. Now that COVID-19 (a coronavirus) is spreading around the world, there has been some controversy in the USA about whether or not wearing a face masks is necessary or effective. From my own knowledge and experience, I can say unequivocally that wearing a face mask should be very important to everybody right now (in enclosed public places). It’s somewhat alarming for me to see that virtually no one is currently wearing a mask inside public places. Frankly, the policy in business should be that all employees working indoors must wear a mask in the workplace. The public should be firmly advised to wear a mask inside all public places!
When I worked in health care, there was a strict policy that any employee that does not get a flu shot must wear a face mask in all patient areas.
The unfortunate thing right now is that masks are in very high demand and there are hardly even enough masks just the health care industry. Fortunately, people that cannot find factory-made masks can make their own mask out of cloth, which is better than nothing.
The serious problem with the flu is when a contagious person is coughing inside an enclosed area. The virus then becomes airborne and can remain suspended for a period of time; Others nearby can inhale the bug or get it into their eyes. In a hospital, active COVID-19 isolation is employing a “space suit” of protective attire and a powered air purifying respirator (PAPR).
We can all help reduce the spread of this virus by voluntarily wearing masks in public places.

snippet.textDisplay:
This virus not only changed all the life styles in Korea, but also makes people nervous every day.
Please... everyone in the world should think seriously. Every day I go to work, I feel a little scared.
I also thought about quitting the company for fear that my son in my family might spread the disease because of me.
No vaccine is the biggest problem.
Children seem to be resistant to viruses. But imagine the children passing the virus to older people. This is a matter of family destruction.
This is really scary.
Because older people, people who are vulnerable to sanitation, just feel too easy to infect
And people with diabetes, heart disease, etc. should be really careful, even if you don't have to tell them.
